00:35:51.030 --> 00:35:53.530
-When I was born death,
my mother cried.

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:56.680
She really did not
see a future.

00:35:56.680 --> 00:35:58.736
-The doctors said, he would
never amount to anything.

00:35:58.736 --> 00:36:01.065
His mental capacity would
be little to none.

00:36:01.065 --> 00:36:02.570
And you should probably
give him up

00:36:02.570 --> 00:36:04.010
and think about adoption.

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:08.000
-I really didn't even know that
something was going on,

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:10.500
that there was something
wrong in my mind.

00:36:10.500 --> 00:36:13.456
-I didn't know the
word transsexual.

00:36:13.456 --> 00:36:16.290
The word transgender hadn't
even been invented yet.

00:36:16.290 --> 00:36:18.600
-He has a mentor
that helps him.

00:36:18.600 --> 00:36:20.440
No biting, Chris.

00:36:20.440 --> 00:36:24.270
Chris probably had one of the
worst diagnosis ever-- self

00:36:24.270 --> 00:36:28.320
injurious, swollen intestines,
poisons in him system, mental

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:30.300
retardation, severe autism.

00:36:30.300 --> 00:36:33.316
And I was pretty much told to
put him in an institution.

00:36:33.316 --> 00:36:35.775
-When I was born, my
mom refused to see

00:36:35.775 --> 00:36:36.140
me for three days.

00:36:36.140 --> 00:36:37.260
She was scared.

00:36:37.260 --> 00:36:40.430
-Before I transitioned, I
just wasn't all there.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:44.100
I couldn't quite share
my feelings.

00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:49.250
I couldn't quite be a full
member of the family.

00:36:49.250 --> 00:36:50.690
-You sort of get what you get.

00:36:50.690 --> 00:36:51.850
And you go from there.

00:36:51.850 --> 00:36:54.300
And it's your choice.

00:36:54.300 --> 00:36:56.210
You want to make the best of it,
you make the best of it.

00:36:56.210 --> 00:36:57.735
You want to make the
worst of it, throw

00:36:57.735 --> 00:36:59.100
yourself a pity party.

00:36:59.100 --> 00:37:01.240
-I set out to write a book which
was about how people

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:02.680
found meaning in difficulty.

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:05.180
It's hard for the kids
to accept themselves.

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:07.600
It's hard for their families
to accept them.

00:37:07.600 --> 00:37:10.950
It's hard for the larger society
to accept the kids and

00:37:10.950 --> 00:37:11.970
their parents.

00:37:11.970 --> 00:37:13.285
All of it is a struggle.

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:19.630
I wouldn't ever want to pretend
that these aren't

00:37:19.630 --> 00:37:20.990
difficult lives.

00:37:20.990 --> 00:37:22.480
They are very difficult lives.

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:25.310
They're full of pain
and complexity.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:29.380
-We have joints and bones that
are twisted and distorted.

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:32.410
So our life is marred with
a lot of surgeries.

00:37:32.410 --> 00:37:34.350
Myself, I've had 30.

00:37:34.350 --> 00:37:36.140
-And there was one guy that
I had a crush on.

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.230
He said to me, why
do you lisp?

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:41.800
And my heart would crush.

00:37:41.800 --> 00:37:43.250
-Chris did not communicate.

00:37:43.250 --> 00:37:44.290
He didn't sit down.

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:45.200
He didn't put on clothes.

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:46.200
He wouldn't go outside.

00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:47.670
He ate the walls.

00:37:47.670 --> 00:37:48.430
He ate the table.

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:49.075
He at the rug.

00:37:49.075 --> 00:37:54.580
-I could feel the back of my
neck popping and sizzling.

00:37:54.580 --> 00:37:56.280
Like my head was just
heating up.

00:37:56.280 --> 00:37:57.450
-We couldn't eat in the home.

00:37:57.450 --> 00:37:58.420
We couldn't have lights on.

00:37:58.420 --> 00:37:59.570
We couldn't have the TV on.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:03.490
If I coughed, he would run
downstairs and punch me.

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:08.600
-I actually felt that I was a
surgeon, and I felt I had to

00:38:08.600 --> 00:38:13.010
literally extricate the demon
from inside of my body.

00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:15.760
-When I started this book, I
knew that I was going to be

00:38:15.760 --> 00:38:18.370
looking at a lot of desperate
situations.

00:38:18.370 --> 00:38:22.760
-And I would do that by cutting
and burning myself.

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:25.890
-What I didn't know was how much
joy I was going to find.

00:38:25.890 --> 00:38:29.080
-When I was born, my dad
said, he looks cute.

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:31.760
He's just got a big head
and little arms.

00:38:31.760 --> 00:38:34.180
The funny thing is I still
look that way.

00:38:34.180 --> 00:38:38.530
-And the relief that came over
my face when I heard that

00:38:38.530 --> 00:38:41.100
there was a name to what
was going on with me.

00:38:41.100 --> 00:38:42.570
-I used what God gave me.

00:38:42.570 --> 00:38:46.010
God didn't give me
legs to run.

00:38:46.010 --> 00:38:50.010
He didn't give me arms to
play football with.

00:38:50.010 --> 00:38:54.760
He gave me a brain, and He gave
me a heart, and I try to

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:57.020
use both of those things
to the fullest.

00:38:57.020 --> 00:39:00.570
-The thing I've learned most
over the years is to be a

00:39:00.570 --> 00:39:01.640
parent first.

00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:05.090
I thought to myself, if he's
happy, if he stops hurting

00:39:05.090 --> 00:39:09.620
himself, if I can hug him, that
would be the greatest

00:39:09.620 --> 00:39:10.600
gift in life.

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:14.670
-It's kind of pretty sure that
I'm going to have obstacles,

00:39:14.670 --> 00:39:16.100
but I would have had
them anyway.

00:39:16.100 --> 00:39:19.220
-I know my dad is very,
very proud of me.

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:25.170
Because I went on a
journey that he

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:26.772
never dreamed possible.

00:39:26.772 --> 00:39:33.882
-I don't think of myself
as a schizophrenic.

00:39:33.882 --> 00:39:35.070
I am Susan.

00:39:35.070 --> 00:39:37.970
-There really isn't any
definition and what's normal,

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:42.720
or not normal, or far from the
tree, or right under the tree.

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:45.970
-I'm lucky to have had her in
this particular period of

00:39:45.970 --> 00:39:46.390
time.

00:39:46.390 --> 00:39:46.670
-I'm lucky too.

00:39:46.670 --> 00:39:48.934
-And thank you.

00:39:48.934 --> 00:39:52.005
-The love that parents have
for their children--

00:39:52.005 --> 00:39:53.765
-I guess we are pretty
lucky, huh?

00:39:53.765 --> 00:39:54.675
-Yes, Mom.

00:39:54.675 --> 00:39:55.820
We are.

00:39:55.820 --> 00:39:57.620
- --can see them through
an enormous amount.

00:40:17.997 --> 00:40:19.488
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:40:19.488 --> 00:40:24.864
AUDIENCE: I was just curious in
terms of the parents that

00:40:24.864 --> 00:40:29.256
you characterized as heroic
versus the parents, who

00:40:29.256 --> 00:40:32.184
without sort of that judgment,
maybe we characterize as less

00:40:32.184 --> 00:40:33.840
than heroic.

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:37.800
Did you see any commonalities
between those two groups in

00:40:37.800 --> 00:40:39.217
terms of their attitude?

00:40:39.217 --> 00:40:42.292
Or what did it take for
parents to be heroic?

00:40:42.292 --> 00:40:44.420
Did you see any common things
among those parents?

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:47.210
ANDREW SOLOMON: Well, I should
first of all say that I have a

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:49.800
lot of empathy for parents who
have got children like this

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:52.590
and are not having the easiest
and best time with them.

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:54.450
I think it's a tall order,
and it's tough.

00:40:54.450 --> 00:40:57.130
And so I wouldn't want to come
down against the other.

00:40:57.130 --> 00:41:00.680
But what I found mostly was this
thing of searching for

00:41:00.680 --> 00:41:04.100
meaning and trying to see a way
in which having this child

00:41:04.100 --> 00:41:06.310
had forced them to grow
and to change.

00:41:06.310 --> 00:41:10.050
So I think it's the issue
really with difficulty

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:12.540
altogether in life, is that you
can either rail against it

00:41:12.540 --> 00:41:15.740
and be angry at it, or you can
accept whatever difficulty

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:18.830
can't, in fact, be ameliorated
and just decide that's you're

00:41:18.830 --> 00:41:21.190
going to look for a way
to build something

00:41:21.190 --> 00:41:22.600
positive out of it so.

00:41:22.600 --> 00:41:25.555
When you had the mother of that
dwarf saying our child

00:41:25.555 --> 00:41:28.050
had this extraordinary light,
and he did these things.

00:41:28.050 --> 00:41:30.020
Or even when you had the mother
who said when she

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:33.260
buried her child that she had
come to love him, it's the

00:41:33.260 --> 00:41:36.070
onset, it's the openness to
falling in love with your own

00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:39.050
child that I think makes an
enormous difference in the

00:41:39.050 --> 00:41:42.210
sense that you've been put on
this path that isn't the one

00:41:42.210 --> 00:41:45.550
you would have chosen, but
nonetheless, offers rewards

00:41:45.550 --> 00:41:47.460
which are perhaps different
from the rewards you

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:48.450
anticipated.

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:50.670
There's a famous little passage
that was written by

00:41:50.670 --> 00:41:52.930
Emily Kingsley who's the mother
of a child with Down

00:41:52.930 --> 00:41:55.380
syndrome called "Welcome to
Holland," which I have

00:41:55.380 --> 00:41:57.940
reproduced in this book that we
may have to take it out for

00:41:57.940 --> 00:42:00.880
the edition published in the
Netherlands, but in which she

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:03.810
says that having children is
like planning a trip to Italy

00:42:03.810 --> 00:42:07.450
but having a child like hers is
when they are coming into

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:10.130
land and you're told actually,
you're landing in Holland.

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:13.000
And you have to recognize
that you will never see

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:14.250
Michelangelo's David.

00:42:14.250 --> 00:42:17.710
And you will never get to sort
of walk through the forum or

00:42:17.710 --> 00:42:20.400
take a Gondola in Venice, but
actually the place you're in

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:22.080
is full of Rembrandts
and tulips.

00:42:22.080 --> 00:42:24.700
And if you can learn to
appreciate those other things

00:42:24.700 --> 00:42:27.260
instead, no matter how much
you may still regret not

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:29.980
getting to Italy, you can find
a lot of joy in Holland.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:33.260
And it's a little cutesy, but it
actually, I think, sums up

00:42:33.260 --> 00:42:35.210
a lot of the attitude
in question.

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:35.380
Yeah?

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:39.029
AUDIENCE: You talked about a
couple of quotes about in view

00:42:39.029 --> 00:42:43.086
of homosexuality and Down
syndrome back in the '60s and

00:42:43.086 --> 00:42:47.870
'70s and how society
has evolved.

00:42:47.870 --> 00:42:50.289
What do you think has
contributed to that?

00:42:50.289 --> 00:42:55.054
And what do you think will be
your prediction of how things

00:42:55.054 --> 00:42:59.070
will be 30 or 40 years from now
in terms of perception and

00:42:59.070 --> 00:43:01.895
experience with different
children?

00:43:01.895 --> 00:43:03.540
ANDREW SOLOMON: That's an
excellent question.

00:43:03.540 --> 00:43:07.020
I think the thing that really
has made for the shift has

00:43:07.020 --> 00:43:08.430
been the rights movements.

00:43:08.430 --> 00:43:10.620
And I think the rights movements
have come in a wave.

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:13.650
I think the women's movement and
the original civil rights

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:16.800
movement really set the stage
for the gay rights movement

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:18.340
and the disability
rights movement.

00:43:18.340 --> 00:43:21.600
And that uncomfortable though
people in some of these groups

00:43:21.600 --> 00:43:24.540
may be with people in others of
these groups that actually

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:26.870
it's been a liberalizing
tendency that's taken place

00:43:26.870 --> 00:43:28.290
over a long period of time.

00:43:28.290 --> 00:43:32.420
You know, met also with a
certain amount of opposition,

00:43:32.420 --> 00:43:35.000
but there's been more and more
of a recognition that there is

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:38.410
a diversity of experience that
constitutes human experience.

00:43:38.410 --> 00:43:42.060
In terms of where we'll be in 30
or 40 years, I'd be really

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:44.400
curious, because I feel like
where we are now in terms of

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:47.050
gay rights was unimaginable
30 or 40 years ago.

00:43:47.050 --> 00:43:49.770
And will we continue to go
in the same direction?

00:43:49.770 --> 00:43:52.620
Will more and more ways of being
become acceptable, or

00:43:52.620 --> 00:43:54.950
will the medical progress we're
making cause us once

00:43:54.950 --> 00:43:58.360
more to narrow the definition
of what it is to be human?

00:43:58.360 --> 00:43:59.590
History has gone in waves.

00:43:59.590 --> 00:44:02.420
It's unusual for there to be
nothing but steady progress

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:03.970
over a long period of time.

00:44:03.970 --> 00:44:06.280
I don't know which of the things
that we now experience

00:44:06.280 --> 00:44:09.550
as an illness will in
the end be conceived

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:11.420
primarily as an identity.

00:44:11.420 --> 00:44:13.570
What I know is that it will
not all be the same

00:44:13.570 --> 00:44:14.610
as it is right now.

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:17.380
So there are things that right
now we think of as totally

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:20.790
bizarre that in 40 years ago
might seem to people to be

00:44:20.790 --> 00:44:22.300
perfectly ordinary.

00:44:22.300 --> 00:44:26.240
Will polygamy be an ordinary
thing in 40 years?

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:29.760
I don't have any crystal ball
to say what the things are,

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:34.860
but I think there are things
that the standards of sexual

00:44:34.860 --> 00:44:37.490
contact between adults and
children, will things that now

00:44:37.490 --> 00:44:38.985
seem acceptable become
unacceptable.

00:44:38.985 --> 00:44:42.480
Will things that now seem
unacceptable seem more

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:43.590
acceptable?

00:44:43.590 --> 00:44:47.720
Will there be more integration
of people with different kinds

00:44:47.720 --> 00:44:50.640
of intelligence?

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:52.270
Will autism continue
to increase?

00:44:52.270 --> 00:44:54.780
Will the autism rights movement
mean that we more and

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:57.880
more accept that many people
are not neurotypical and we

00:44:57.880 --> 00:45:00.260
accept the motor social
interaction that seems to come

00:45:00.260 --> 00:45:01.490
most readily to them?

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:03.050
All of it is unclear.

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:04.860
So I don't know what it
will be, but I do

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:05.850
know it will be different.

00:45:05.850 --> 00:45:07.420
And where we are is
so different from

00:45:07.420 --> 00:45:08.750
where we were before.

00:45:08.750 --> 00:45:10.420
And where we're headed
will be different.

00:45:10.420 --> 00:45:12.570
And I think I should say that
part of the reason that

00:45:12.570 --> 00:45:16.190
everything has changed now, and
there may not be another

00:45:16.190 --> 00:45:19.160
radical revision like this, but
is because of the advent

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:23.380
of the internet and the ability,
if I may be allowed

00:45:23.380 --> 00:45:26.560
in this context to say so, to
figure out what the quality is

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:28.480
you have and Google it.

00:45:28.480 --> 00:45:33.590
All you have to do is to put in
child with multiple severe

00:45:33.590 --> 00:45:36.580
disabilities, and you've got
thousands and thousands of

00:45:36.580 --> 00:45:40.000
articles and links and means
of meeting other parents.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:41.830
So a lot of these conditions
people

00:45:41.830 --> 00:45:44.010
experienced in terrible isolation.

00:45:44.010 --> 00:45:46.090
And now they experience
them in community.

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:48.470
And that shift has
been enormous.

00:45:48.470 --> 00:45:51.770
And once you have a community,
you can fight for tolerance.

00:45:51.770 --> 00:45:56.688
So that has also been
a gigantic shift.

00:45:56.688 --> 00:45:58.152
Yeah?

00:45:58.152 --> 00:46:00.348
AUDIENCE: My question
sort of comes--

00:46:00.348 --> 00:46:03.032
I'm not a parent and I haven't
