And I think they actually put a
child into a care facility.

00:46:46.979 --> 00:46:49.168
But I wonder if you could--

00:46:49.168 --> 00:46:53.466
if you don't mind explaining as
much as you can maybe, the

00:46:53.466 --> 00:46:54.963
choices that the parents
go through.

00:46:54.963 --> 00:46:59.121
I still have a hard time
understanding how people get

00:46:59.121 --> 00:47:02.947
rid of their old life and
get self-directed again.

00:47:02.947 --> 00:47:06.939
I wake up and have breakfast in
the morning versus oh, what

00:47:06.939 --> 00:47:08.436
does my child want.

00:47:08.436 --> 00:47:10.307
Again, I'm not a parent so maybe
it changes no matter

00:47:10.307 --> 00:47:10.931
what anyway.

00:47:10.931 --> 00:47:13.925
But I just wonder how
do they do that?

00:47:13.925 --> 00:47:14.923
And how does it make sense?

00:47:14.923 --> 00:47:17.990
And how are they crazy?

00:47:17.990 --> 00:47:19.020
ANDREW SOLOMON: Well, some
of them are crazy.

00:47:19.020 --> 00:47:20.800
As you observed, the particular
family you're

00:47:20.800 --> 00:47:25.620
talking about all ended up in
intensive psychiatric care.

00:47:25.620 --> 00:47:28.550
A lot of the time, it's not
something that people have

00:47:28.550 --> 00:47:30.100
thought through before
they have children.

00:47:30.100 --> 00:47:32.050
And then you have children with
these kinds of special

00:47:32.050 --> 00:47:36.850
needs, and they really require
you to make this radical shift

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:39.370
in your way of life partly just
because of the actual

00:47:39.370 --> 00:47:41.150
physical demands on your time.

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:44.820
So especially for people who
don't have enormous economic

00:47:44.820 --> 00:47:48.360
resources and can't outsource
a lot of the early care, you

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:50.300
have a child who's
got a disability.

00:47:50.300 --> 00:47:51.850
The child is being
operated on.

00:47:51.850 --> 00:47:53.040
You're stuck in the hospital.

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:54.810
You're stuck going
back and forth.

00:47:54.810 --> 00:47:55.940
You take the child home.

00:47:55.940 --> 00:47:58.000
He requires 24-hour care.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.280
I mean, a lot of them don't sit
and make the decision, I

00:48:00.280 --> 00:48:02.870
will nobly and heroically give
up my life in favor of this

00:48:02.870 --> 00:48:04.010
other way of being.

00:48:04.010 --> 00:48:05.040
But rather simply--

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:07.840
[VIDEO PLAYING]

00:48:07.840 --> 00:48:10.885
ANDREW SOLOMON: Well,
there's the--

00:48:10.885 --> 00:48:17.840
[VIDEO PLAYING]

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:19.090
ANDREW SOLOMON: OK.

00:48:20.710 --> 00:48:24.090
If we could get the picture,
that would be great.

00:48:24.090 --> 00:48:29.642
[VIDEO PLAYING]

00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:37.320
ANDREW SOLOMON: Yes.

00:48:37.320 --> 00:48:37.850
Where were we?

00:48:37.850 --> 00:48:40.900
So making the huge sacrifices,
I think it's really a process

00:48:40.900 --> 00:48:42.810
in which people are dragged
kicking and screaming.

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:45.120
And then they make sense of
it a little bit later on.

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:48.560
That's really how it begins.

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:48.930
Yes?

00:48:48.930 --> 00:48:51.834
AUDIENCE: In the introduction
you talked a little bit about

00:48:51.834 --> 00:48:54.738
some of the identities you
thought you might discuss in

00:48:54.738 --> 00:48:57.158
the book that were
not included.

00:48:57.158 --> 00:49:00.000
And I was wondering if you could
talk a little bit about

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:01.540
the process and how far you went
in your research and then

00:49:01.540 --> 00:49:02.860
why you decided not
to pursue those.

00:49:02.860 --> 00:49:06.856
And whether those may become
magazine articles later or a

00:49:06.856 --> 00:49:07.832
second book.

00:49:07.832 --> 00:49:09.300
I don't know.

00:49:09.300 --> 00:49:10.950
ANDREW SOLOMON: Someone just
actually asked me, they want

00:49:10.950 --> 00:49:14.150
to do a sort of little limited
edition book with some of

00:49:14.150 --> 00:49:16.050
those stories in it.

00:49:16.050 --> 00:49:19.920
I started off looking at dozens
and dozens of topics.

00:49:19.920 --> 00:49:23.630
And I narrowed them down--
partly, I chose the ones in

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:29.010
which people had in which
I heard amazing stories.

00:49:29.010 --> 00:49:30.880
And so some of them
came really out of

00:49:30.880 --> 00:49:32.130
the narrative content.

00:49:32.130 --> 00:49:34.850
But I also felt that if I was
talking about deafness, even

00:49:34.850 --> 00:49:36.970
though blindness is very
different, I didn't really

00:49:36.970 --> 00:49:40.400
need to blindness because
the issues were similar.

00:49:40.400 --> 00:49:44.290
And if I was doing dwarfism,
I didn't really need to do

00:49:44.290 --> 00:49:48.010
gigantism because a lot of the
underlying issues-- even if

00:49:48.010 --> 00:49:49.835
the medical issues were actually
quite different-- a

00:49:49.835 --> 00:49:51.760
lot of the underlying issues
were the same.

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:53.900
There was a lot of doing that
kind of elimination and then

00:49:53.900 --> 00:49:56.100
there was a certain amount of
just slashing things because

00:49:56.100 --> 00:49:58.790
it's quite a chunky
book as it is.

00:49:58.790 --> 00:50:02.360
And I was worried that if I
tried to make it any longer,

00:50:02.360 --> 00:50:04.300
it would become unwieldy
and unreadable.

00:50:04.300 --> 00:50:07.050
So there were some that just
went for that reason.

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:11.660
But there were so many amazing
stories that I heard even in

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:13.490
these other areas.

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:16.960
And the idea of giving them
up, it was difficult.

00:50:16.960 --> 00:50:18.010
It came at a cost.

00:50:18.010 --> 00:50:20.520
I gave up individual families
within each of the chapters,

00:50:20.520 --> 00:50:22.460
and I also gave up
whole chapters.

00:50:22.460 --> 00:50:23.940
But I wanted to cover
a spectrum.

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:26.573
And I felt that if we started
with deafness, which is

00:50:26.573 --> 00:50:29.270
probably the most readily
accepted as an identity and

00:50:29.270 --> 00:50:32.230
which is in some ways for people
who grow up using sign

00:50:32.230 --> 00:50:37.100
fluently, the one that has the
least long term, obvious

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:38.120
detriment in their lives.

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:40.100
We started with the deafness
and dwarfism really.

00:50:40.100 --> 00:50:41.790
And then we went on to
these other things.

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:44.060
And if we looked at the
ones that are disease

00:50:44.060 --> 00:50:46.540
constructions, which is the
first half of the book, and

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:48.650
the ones that are more identity
constructions, which

00:50:48.650 --> 00:50:51.000
are the second half, I
hoped I was being as

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:52.592
representative as possible.

00:50:52.592 --> 00:50:52.990
Yeah.

00:50:52.990 --> 00:50:54.478
In the back.

00:50:54.478 --> 00:50:59.438
AUDIENCE: I'm curious when you
set out to write the book, and

00:50:59.438 --> 00:51:00.430
you talked a little bit about
it, you touched on it here

00:51:00.430 --> 00:51:01.918
some of it in an initial
publication.

00:51:01.918 --> 00:51:07.374
But was this a bit of like a
parental litmus test for you?

00:51:07.374 --> 00:51:10.846
Were you sort of looking for a
reason not to be a parent?

00:51:10.846 --> 00:51:15.310
I mean, I don't mean to sound
simplistic, but was it a way

00:51:15.310 --> 00:51:17.790
to talk yourself out of it?

00:51:17.790 --> 00:51:20.130
ANDREW SOLOMON: It was certainly
not a way to talk

00:51:20.130 --> 00:51:21.340
myself out of being a parent.

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:22.570
I wanted to be a parent.

00:51:22.570 --> 00:51:24.580
I'd always wanted
to be a parent.

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:27.430
And I had at various stages
struggled with the issue of

00:51:27.430 --> 00:51:29.400
being gay mostly because I
thought it would prevent me

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:30.320
from being a parent.

00:51:30.320 --> 00:51:32.920
So that had been
kind of steady.

00:51:32.920 --> 00:51:35.160
When I realized I could be a
parent, of course, I then went

00:51:35.160 --> 00:51:38.590
into a panic mode, but that
was a little later on.

00:51:38.590 --> 00:51:45.970
But I think that it was a means
of looking squarely at

00:51:45.970 --> 00:51:50.435
what parenthood entailed and
realizing that it was doable.

00:51:50.435 --> 00:51:52.550
So I think in a way,
it was the reverse.

00:51:52.550 --> 00:51:55.210
It was a way of saying, I'm
terribly anxious about how I

00:51:55.210 --> 00:51:58.260
would deal with having a child
who's different in some way.

00:51:58.260 --> 00:52:01.260
I know that I am a child who
was different in some way.

00:52:01.260 --> 00:52:03.480
I know that it was hard for my
parents, though we all got

00:52:03.480 --> 00:52:05.550
through it and came out
happily in the end.

00:52:05.550 --> 00:52:09.066
You know, would I be able to do
it and how can I learn how

00:52:09.066 --> 00:52:11.780
to do it in case I have a child
who presents what are,

00:52:11.780 --> 00:52:14.000
for me, challenges like
the ones that I

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:15.881
posed for my own parents.

00:52:15.881 --> 00:52:18.350
And it was really kind
of the focus.

00:52:18.350 --> 00:52:20.140
So yeah.

00:52:20.140 --> 00:52:22.450
But I mean, I don't think I
realized that I was writing it

00:52:22.450 --> 00:52:23.570
until well into it.

00:52:23.570 --> 00:52:26.902
AUDIENCE: But I was wondering
if your parents are still

00:52:26.902 --> 00:52:31.246
alive, and if so, how they
responded to the book and how

00:52:31.246 --> 00:52:33.380
that journey has
been for them.

00:52:33.380 --> 00:52:35.890
ANDREW SOLOMON: My mother died
22 years ago, but my father is

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:39.750
still alive, and he's been
immensely supportive of the

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:41.950
book all the way through.

00:52:41.950 --> 00:52:43.680
He read all of the
drafts and so on.

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:45.200
He's been a big supporter.

00:52:45.200 --> 00:52:47.860
I think there were things in it
that were difficult, but he

00:52:47.860 --> 00:52:50.870
said that he felt like
ultimately it expressed a real

00:52:50.870 --> 00:52:53.420
truth about ways in which we
had all struggled and how

00:52:53.420 --> 00:52:54.210
we've made it through.

00:52:54.210 --> 00:52:56.350
So it had a very good
response to it.

00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:57.338
Thanks.

00:52:57.338 --> 00:52:59.314
Yeah, yes?

00:52:59.314 --> 00:53:01.784
AUDIENCE: My question
is a kind of

00:53:01.784 --> 00:53:03.034
writing process question.

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:07.586
Was there a moment or was there
sort of a process where

00:53:07.586 --> 00:53:09.216
you committed to the fact that
this was going to just be like

00:53:09.216 --> 00:53:15.084
a huge endeavor and one single
thing rather than a collection

00:53:15.084 --> 00:53:18.751
of articles about identity
politics that were sort of

00:53:18.751 --> 00:53:19.500
different outlooks?

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:21.430
ANDREW SOLOMON: So I was always
clear that I wanted to

00:53:21.430 --> 00:53:22.590
keep it as one book.

00:53:22.590 --> 00:53:24.500
There was discussion about
whether it should be broken

00:53:24.500 --> 00:53:26.710
into two books, and I felt like,
well, I have insights

00:53:26.710 --> 00:53:29.610
within each chapter, the primary
insight is the uniting

00:53:29.610 --> 00:53:32.030
insight, and if we broke it
up, that would get lost.

00:53:32.030 --> 00:53:33.175
And that was the problem.

00:53:33.175 --> 00:53:34.030
And the complexity--

00:53:34.030 --> 00:53:36.000
actually, I'm now looking at
the possibility of making a

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:36.960
documentary film--

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:41.180
is how do you sort of squash all
of this into 90 minutes or

00:53:41.180 --> 00:53:43.660
something like that and not
have it become completely

00:53:43.660 --> 00:53:44.620
incoherent.

00:53:44.620 --> 00:53:46.750
I don't think I understood
the extent to it.

00:53:46.750 --> 00:53:48.760
I mean, I saw it as a book that
was going to take me 3

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:50.060
years and it took me 11.

00:53:50.060 --> 00:53:56.040
So it became clear as I went
along that for me to feel like

00:53:56.040 --> 00:53:57.995
I could really speak with
authority on these topics, I

00:53:57.995 --> 00:53:59.600
had to learn a huge amount.

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:01.930
I was thinking, if a book
expresses more than 10% of

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:03.960
what you know about the thing
you're writing about, it's not

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:06.120
going to be a very
convincing book.

00:54:06.120 --> 00:54:08.800
And I think if I understood how
huge it was going to be, I

00:54:08.800 --> 00:54:10.080
would never have
undertaken it.

00:54:10.080 --> 00:54:12.970
But then once I was in the
middle, it was a little like

00:54:12.970 --> 00:54:13.990
the Vietnam War.

00:54:13.990 --> 00:54:15.890
I sort of thought I put
in so much already, I

00:54:15.890 --> 00:54:17.420
have to keep going.

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:20.264
So that was kind of
the feeling of it.

00:54:20.264 --> 00:54:21.590
Yeah.

00:54:21.590 --> 00:54:24.425
Anyone else?

00:54:24.425 --> 00:54:24.850
OK.

00:54:24.850 --> 00:54:28.030
Well, thank you all so much
for coming to this in the

00:54:28.030 --> 00:54:29.080
middle of your busy day.

00:54:29.080 --> 00:54:29.680
Thank you.

00:54:29.680 --> 00:54:30.280
Thank you.

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:33.548
[APPLAUSE]

